2 Trends in cases

2.1 Data

Data will be easier to handle if first converted to an incidence2 object, as asmodee will recognize these inputs and handle de stratification by country for us. We also add the weekday variable, and retain only the last 6 weeks of data.


cases_i <- dat %>%
  incidence(date,
            counts = c(cases, tests, deaths),
            groups = c(report_country)) %>%
  mutate(weekend = day_of_week(date_index)) %>% # add weekday
  keep_last(7 * 7) %>%
  mutate(weekday = factor(weekdays(date_index)))

2.2 Model generators

Here we use some ad-hoc code to handle cases where the training set contains not one, but 2 temporal trends. The proposed solution is to duplicate each candidate model of the form model(response ~ xxx + time) into:

  1. the same model
  2. a set of k models in the form: model(response ~ xxx + change_k:time + time) where change_k is a binary qualitative variable marking before/after day k; the set of models generated will explore various values of k

2.2.1 Adding binary variables to the data

Here we add the change_k variables mentioned above; considering we have 6 weeks of data in total, including 5 for training, we allow k to vary from day 8 to day 28.


cases_i <- cases_i %>%
  mutate(day = as.integer(date_index - min(date_index)))

min_k <- 9
max_k <- 25
k_values <- min_k:max_k
change_k_df <- lapply(k_values,
                       function(k)
                         cases_i %>%
                         group_by(report_country) %>%
                         transmute(if_else(day <= k, "before", "after")) %>%
                         pull(2)) %>%
  data.frame() %>%
  tibble() %>%
  setNames(paste0("change_", k_values))

cases_i <- cases_i %>%
  bind_cols(change_k_df)

2.2.2 Define split models


model_grid <- expand.grid(
    c("", "tests"), # with/without tests
    "date_index", # time effect
    c("", "weekend", "weekday"), # optional offsets
    c("", paste("date_index*change", k_values, sep = "_")) # optional split
)

## convert to text
predictors_txt <- model_grid %>%
  apply(1, paste, collapse = " + ")

## cleanup
predictors_txt <- gsub("(\\+[ ]*)+[ ]*\\+", " + ", predictors_txt) # +... + -> +
predictors_txt <- sub("^[ ]*\\+", "", predictors_txt) # heading +
predictors_txt <- sub("\\+[ ]*$", "", predictors_txt) # trailing +
predictors_txt <- sub("^[ ]+", "", predictors_txt) # heading spaces
predictors_txt <- sub("[ ]+$", "", predictors_txt) # trailing spaces
predictors_txt <- sub("[ ]+", " ", predictors_txt) # multiple spaces

## add constant models
predictors_txt <- c("1", predictors_txt)

2.3 Candidate models

Candidate models are generated to include:

  • Poisson GLM or NegBin GLM
  • combinations of:
    • with date effect
    • with / without testing effect
    • with / without weekend effect
    • with / without weekday effect
    • with / without trend shift effect (different slope before/after) with changing points on day 8, 9, … or 28 (first training day is day 0)

models_txt  <- c(
    ## sprintf("lm_model(cases ~ %s)", predictors_txt), # linear models
    sprintf("glm_model(cases ~ %s, family = gaussian)", predictors_txt) , # Gaussian GLMs
    sprintf("glm_nb_model(cases ~ %s)", predictors_txt) # NegBin GLMs
)

length(models_txt)
## [1] 218
head(models_txt)
## [1] "glm_model(cases ~ 1, family = gaussian)"                            "glm_model(cases ~ date_index, family = gaussian)"                  
## [3] "glm_model(cases ~ tests + date_index, family = gaussian)"           "glm_model(cases ~ date_index + weekend, family = gaussian)"        
## [5] "glm_model(cases ~ tests + date_index + weekend, family = gaussian)" "glm_model(cases ~ date_index + weekday, family = gaussian)"
tail(models_txt)
## [1] "glm_nb_model(cases ~ date_index +  date_index*change_25)"                  "glm_nb_model(cases ~ tests + date_index  +  date_index*change_25)"        
## [3] "glm_nb_model(cases ~ date_index + weekend + date_index*change_25)"         "glm_nb_model(cases ~ tests + date_index + weekend + date_index*change_25)"
## [5] "glm_nb_model(cases ~ date_index + weekday + date_index*change_25)"         "glm_nb_model(cases ~ tests + date_index + weekday + date_index*change_25)"

cases_models <- lapply(models_txt, function(e) eval(parse(text = e)))

2.4 Run ASMODEE

Case data can be problematic because of occasional artifactual ‘zeros’, which reflect the absence of reporting on a given day, typically followed by a higher case count reflecting the backlog. Unfortunately, this often throws off the Negbin GLM, which is most of the time our best option: Poisson GLM drastically under-estimates variance and sees most points as outliers, and Gaussian GLM can predict negative numbers.

To circumvent the issue, we use the new feature from i2extras called flag_low_counts(), which we use to set to NA all counts below a certain threshold (here, 1/100 of the median). This is done separately for each country.


# run asmodee
cases_res <- cases_i %>%
  asmodee(cases_models, k = 7,
          simulate_pi = FALSE)

# keep only successful runs
to_keep <- vapply(cases_res$output, inherits, logical(1), "trendbreaker")
cases_res <- cases_res %>%
  filter(to_keep)

3 Growth rates

3.1 Growth rates

These estimates of daily growth rates are based on negative binomial GLM fitted to the last 3 weeks of data. Positive values indicate epidemic growth, and negative values indicate decline. Confidence intervals including zero indicate uncertain trends.


#  estimate the growth rates days before (going back: d2 - d10)
## we use future_lapply to speed up computations
df_r  <- future.apply::future_lapply(
  0:params$tadpole_size,
  function(d)
  cases_i %>%
    select(-deaths, -tests) %>% 
    keep_last(3*7 + d) %>%
    keep_first(3*7) %>% 
    fit_curve() %>%
    growth_rate() %>%
    mutate(last_day = d) %>% 
    select(report_country, r, r_lower, r_upper, last_day),
  future.seed = TRUE) %>%
  bind_rows() %>%
  mutate(type = case_when(r_lower > 0 ~ "growth",
                          r_upper < 0 ~ "decline",
                          TRUE ~ "uncertain"),
         type = factor(type, levels = c("growth", "uncertain", "decline")))

countries_missing_r <- setdiff(analysed_countries, df_r$report_country)

# handle countries with no results
if (length(countries_missing_r)) {
  msg <- paste0("Estimates of *r* could not be produced for the following countries:\n",
                paste(countries_missing_r, collapse = ", "))
  message(msg)
  notes <- c(notes, gsub("\n", "<br>", msg))
}

scale_type <- scale_color_manual(
  "Incidence trend",
  values = c(growth = "#EC6446",
             decline = "#5DADC6",
             uncertain = "#A9A9A9")
)

df_r %>%
  filter(last_day == 0) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y = report_country, x = r, color = type)) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(xmin = r_lower, xmax = r_upper)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_type +
#  scale_x_continuous(labels=scales::percent) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = 2, color = "salmon") +
  labs(x = "Daily growth rate (r)", y = "")

4 Overall dynamics

4.1 Merging indicators


# Population by country
df_pop <- dat %>%
  group_by(report_country, iso3) %>%
  summarise(population = mean(population, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'report_country'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

# Cumulative incidence over the last week (going back: w1) per 100k inhabitants
df_recent_incid <- future.apply::future_lapply(
   0:params$tadpole_size,
  function(d)
    cases_i %>%
      keep_last(7 + d) %>%
      keep_first(7) %>% 
      group_by(report_country) %>%
      summarise(n_cases = sum(cases),
                n_deaths = sum(deaths)) %>%
      left_join(df_pop) %>%
      mutate(case_incid_last_week = 1e6 * n_cases / population,
             death_incid_last_week = 1e6 * n_deaths / population,
             last_day = d),
  future.seed = TRUE) %>%
  bind_rows()
## Joining, by = "report_country"
## Joining, by = "report_country"
## Joining, by = "report_country"
## Joining, by = "report_country"
## Joining, by = "report_country"
## Joining, by = "report_country"
## Joining, by = "report_country"
## Joining, by = "report_country"

# Table containing r, incidence per capita, recent increases
df_dynamics <- df_recent_incid %>%
  left_join(df_r) %>%
  left_join(cases_outliers, by = c("report_country" = "Country"))
## Joining, by = c("report_country", "last_day")

# Add data on past peak incidence
minimum_peak <- 0

df_peaks <- dat %>%
  filter(who_region == params$who_region,
         date < (data_stamp - 7)) %>%
  group_by(report_country) %>%
  summarise(incid_peak = max(case_new_7d_100k, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(incid_peak = incid_peak * 10) %>% # incidence per 100k -> 1M
  filter(incid_peak >= minimum_peak)

df_dynamics <- df_dynamics %>%
  left_join(df_peaks, by = "report_country") %>%
  mutate(perc_peak = case_incid_last_week / incid_peak)

# Add info on significance of r (> 0 or < 0)
df_dynamics <- df_dynamics %>%
  mutate(r_signif = if_else(r_lower > 0 | r_upper < 0, "yes", "no"))

# Add 'net_increase' over last week
df_dynamics <- df_dynamics %>%
  mutate(net_increases = n_recent_increases - n_recent_decreases,
         net_increases = if_else(net_increases > 0L, net_increases, 0L))

# data with only current time frame
df_dynamics_current <- df_dynamics %>%
  filter(last_day == 0)

countries_missing_peak <- setdiff(analysed_countries, df_peaks$report_country)

# handle countries with no results
if (length(countries_missing_peak)) {
  msg <- sprintf(
    "Past incidence peaks could not be found (no case previously reported) for the following countries:\n%s",
    minimum_peak,
    paste(countries_missing_peak, collapse = ", "))
  message(msg)
  notes <- c(notes, gsub("\n", "<br>", msg))
}

  theme(legend.position = "bottom",
        axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 18),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12),
        legend.text = element_text(size = 12),
        legend.title = element_text(size = 14),
        legend.title.align = 0.5) +
  guides(
    color = guide_colorsteps(order = 1),
    shape = guide_legend(title.position = "top", order = 2))

5 Test positivity rates (TPR)

5.1 Changes in TPR

The changes in TPR is determined by comparing the last estimated weekly TPR (i.e. including the last available data, excluding artifactual trailing zeros) to the TPR of the week before. TPR estimates as well as the corresponding raw numbers are generated by assemble_data and stored in elr_extras, and are identical to the values reported in the shiny app. We assess the significance of changes by comparing the respective Binomial 95% confidence intervals:


elr_extras <- elr_extras %>%
  mutate(
    tpr_change = case_when(
      is.na(tpr_recent) | is.na(tpr_before) ~ NA_character_,
      tpr_lower_recent >  tpr_upper_before ~ "increasing",
      tpr_upper_recent <  tpr_lower_before ~ "decreasing",
      TRUE ~ "constant"),
    tpr_change = factor(tpr_change,
                        levels = c("decreasing", "constant", "increasing")))

6 Export results

6.1 Create needed directories

We create output directories if they don’t already exist:


target <- here::here("asmodee_outputs")
if (!dir.exists(target)) dir.create(target)

targets <- c("rds", "png", "notes")
for (e in targets) {
  target <- here::here("asmodee_outputs", e)
  if (!dir.exists(target)) dir.create(target)
}

6.2 Save ASMODEE outputs

We export the following products for further uses in other systems, in an object called asmodee_outputs; all objects are stored in /asmodee_outputs/rds/:

  • summary: summary of the ASMODEE results
  • results: outputs of ASMODEE
  • plot_overall_deaths: ggplot2 object of the overall dynamics plot using death per capita on the y-axis
  • plot_overall_peaks: ggplot2 object of the overall dynamics plot using incidence as percentage of historical peak on the y-axis
  • df_dynamics: a data.frame containing all the required info to recreate either global dynamics plots
  • elr_extras: a data.frame containing additional information for countries, including TPR and vaccination coverage
  • timestamp: the timestamp corresponding to the date of the dataset used in the analyses

asmodee_outputs <- list(
  summary = cases_outliers,
  results = cases_res,
  plot_overall_deaths = plot_overall_deaths,
  plot_overall_peaks = plot_overall_peaks,
  df_dynamics = df_dynamics,
  elr_extras = elr_extras,
  timestamp = data_stamp
)

## export asmodee summary
file_name <- sprintf("asmodee_outputs_%s_%s.rds",
                     paste(params$who_region, collapse = "_"),
                     data_stamp)
path_out <- here::here("asmodee_outputs", "rds", file_name)
rio::export(asmodee_outputs, path_out)

## make a copy as latest file
latest_file_name <- sprintf("asmodee_outputs_%s_latest.rds",
                            paste(params$who_region, collapse = "_")
                            )
latest_path_out <- here::here("asmodee_outputs", "rds", latest_file_name)
file.copy(from = path_out, to = latest_path_out, overwrite = TRUE)
## [1] TRUE
